## 1. Copy the bundle into `public/`

**bash**

```bash
cp dist/widget.js public/widget.js
cp dist/widget.css public/widget.css
```

**PowerShell**

```powershell
Copy-Item dist/widget.js public/widget.js
Copy-Item dist/widget.css public/widget.css
```

> Build-time-frozen frontend containers need a **rebuild** before the
> new assets take effect.

## 2. Load the widget from `_document.tsx`

```tsx
import Document, { Html, Head, Main, NextScript } from "next/document";

export default class MyDocument extends Document {
  render() {
    return (
      <Html lang="{{locale}}">
        <Head>
          <link rel="stylesheet" href="/widget.css" />
        </Head>
        <body>
          <Main />
          <NextScript />
          <script
            src="/widget.js"
            defer
            data-backend-url="{{atwBackendOrigin}}"
            data-api-base-url="{{hostApiOrigin}}"
            data-auth-mode="{{authMode}}"
{{#if authTokenKey}}            data-auth-token-key="{{authTokenKey}}"
{{/if}}            data-launcher-position="bottom-right"
            data-locale="{{locale}}"
{{#if loginUrl}}            data-login-url="{{loginUrl}}"
{{/if}}          />
        </body>
      </Html>
    );
  }
}
```

The widget reads its tool catalogue at boot from
`{{atwBackendOrigin}}/tools` — there is no `data-allowed-tools`
attribute (FR-015).

## 3. CORS configuration on your host API

Your host API at `{{hostApiOrigin}}` must accept browser requests from
`{{hostPageOrigin}}`. Headers the widget sends: `Authorization`,
`Content-Type`. Action-manifest verbs: `GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE`.

Required response headers:

- `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: {{hostPageOrigin}}`
- `Access-Control-Allow-Methods: GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE, OPTIONS`
- `Access-Control-Allow-Headers: Authorization, Content-Type`
{{#if (eq authMode "cookie")}}- `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true`
{{/if}}

For Next.js Pages Router, the standard pattern is `pages/api/_cors.ts`
+ a wrapper applied in each API route. For Express/Fastify behind
Pages, use the standard `cors`/`@fastify/cors` middleware with the same
origin/methods/headers. **REPLACE THIS** if your stack is different.

## 4. Run the ATW backend

The emitted `atw/.env.example` already inlines `DATABASE_URL` and
`ALLOWED_ORIGINS={{hostPageOrigin}}` from `project.md`. Paste your
`ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` and start the container.

**bash**

```bash
cp atw/.env.example atw/.env
# edit atw/.env and set ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-...
docker run --rm \
  --env-file atw/.env \
  -p 4000:4000 \
  atw_backend:latest
```

**PowerShell**

```powershell
Copy-Item atw/.env.example atw/.env
# edit atw\.env and set ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-...
docker run --rm `
  --env-file atw/.env `
  -p 4000:4000 `
  atw_backend:latest
```

The backend requires Postgres with the `pgvector` extension; `DATABASE_URL`
in `atw/.env.example` already targets the demo container.

## 5. Static assets

Place `widget.js` and `widget.css` in your Next.js `public/` directory.
Build-time-frozen containers must be rebuilt before changes take effect.

